      <section id="what-is-mcp">
        <h2>1. What is the Model Context Protocol (MCP)?</h2>
        <p>
          As enterprise engineering organizations deploy Large Language Models (LLMs) across internal workflows, the primary bottleneck has shifted from model intelligence to data connectivity. Traditionally, integrating an LLM with corporate data sources, such as PostgreSQL clusters, Jira instances, or custom ERP systems, required writing bespoke, highly coupled Python wrappers and brittle JSON schema tools for every model provider.
        </p>
        <p>
          The <strong>Model Context Protocol (MCP)</strong> solves this N×M integration nightmare by establishing a standardized protocol analogy similar to USB-C for AI applications. Rather than building N custom connectors for M AI hosts, software architects build a single, compliant <strong>MCP Server</strong> that communicates over JSON-RPC 2.0 with any compliant <strong>MCP Host</strong> (such as Claude Desktop, IDE Copilots, or custom enterprise chat applications).
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="architecture-diagram">
        <h2>2. System Architecture: Host, Client, and Server Pipeline</h2>
        <p>
          An enterprise MCP pipeline separates execution context into three well-defined security boundaries:
        </p>
        <pre><code>[MCP Host (e.g. Claude Desktop)] &lt;---&gt; [MCP Client Layer] &lt;--- JSON-RPC 2.0 ---&gt; [Enterprise MCP Server] &lt;--- SQL / API ---&gt; [Corporate Database]</code></pre>
        <p>
          1. **MCP Host**: The application orchestrating user interaction and LLM reasoning.
          2. **MCP Client**: Maintains a stateful protocol connection (via stdio or SSE) with one or more servers.
          3. **MCP Server**: Lightweight, sandboxed programs that expose explicit primitives:
             - **Resources**: Read-only data endpoints (e.g., database schemas, log files, customer profiles).
             - **Tools**: Executable functions that mutate state or perform computation (e.g., execute parameterized SQL query, trigger webhook).
             - **Prompts**: Pre-configured dynamic templates wrapping specific enterprise workflows.
        </p>
      </section>

